From Laura Lemay Subject Re Need advice for riding with someone on pillion In article Bob Wert writes I need some advice on having someone ride pillion with me on my This will be the the first time I've taken anyone for an extended ride read farther than around the block We'll be riding some twisty fairly bumpy roads the Mines Road Loop for you SF Bay Areans An extended ride as a passenger on a Well I hate to be a wet sock but I was a passenger on many bikes for the longest time before I started riding myelf and I grew to hate long rides on sport The passenger seats are not designed for long The passenger positions aren't even usually designed for short I ended up torturing my knees and my back by taking long rides as a passenger on sport One of the reasons I originally liked my current guythingy so much was becase he had a I'd suggest a shorter extended ride at first a short turn in the mountains or some Then see how much pain she's in and proceed from The best advice I'd give a beginning passenger Don't get on the bike until the rider says its OK and work out some sort signal for the rider to tell you when its OK to get After I get on the bike I squeeze my riders hips to tell that I'm ready and at the stop he nods his head to show its OK for me to get Keep your feet on the pegs at all Don't wiggle unless your rider asks you to The best passengers are those which are Echo the movements and lean of your Look over the shoulder thats most comfortable but during turns look over the shoulder on the inside of the Get used to your rider's shifting style Riders use a reasonably consistent shifting style Avoid helmet Helmet bonk is when your rider revs the bike up and then shifts and the sudden change in foreward acceleration causes your helmet to bonk his It gets old real When pulling to a stop put a hand or both hands on the tank to keep your weight from pushing your rider up onto the Putting your hands on the tank is also a good way to stretch your back if you're in pain but I'm told it gets harder to steer in turns if you leave them Switch your hands to the guardrail to stretch your shoulders but be sure and squeeze your thighs while you're doing it so your rider knows you're still The guard rail isn't as safe as holding onto your Don't be afraid to ask for frequent stops if you're in pain or losing feeling in your Passenger seats are not generally designed for Work out some sort of pull over signal Laura Lemay writer of trifles in shadows and blood